[[File:F L Amelung.jpg|thumb|Friedrich Amelung]] '''Friedrich Ludwig Balthasar Amelung''' ({{OldStyleDate|23 March|1842|11 March}} – {{OldStyleDate|20 March|1909|7 March}}) was a [[Baltic German]] [[cultural history|cultural historian]], businessman and [[chess endgame]] composer.
Amelung was born at [[Võisiku]] ({{lang-de|Woiseck}}) manor in [[Governorate of Livonia]] of the [[Russian Empire]] (present-day [[Jõgeva County]] in [[Estonia]]). 1862–1864 he studied [[philosophy]] and [[chemistry]] at the [[University of Tartu|University of Dorpat]]. 1864–1879 and 1885–1902 he was the director of the Rõika-[[Meleski]] mirror factory which he inherited from his father. Amelung published writings about the culture and history of Estonian localities like [[Viljandi]], [[Tallinn]] and [[Põltsamaa]].<ref name=tea>{{cite web|title=Amelung, Friedrich|url=http://www.ents.ee:81/PrintArticle.aspx?aid=2312|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217110404/http://www.ents.ee:81/PrintArticle.aspx?aid=2312|dead-url=yes|archive-date=17 February 2013|publisher=TEA e-Entsüklopeedia|accessdate=29 January 2013|language=Estonian}}</ref>
Amelung was known as a [[chess]] player and a famous chess quiz's author. 1879–1885 he lived in [[Tallinn|Reval]] (now Tallinn) and studied the chess history of the Baltics. Between 1888 and 1908 he edited the [[List of chess periodicals|chess magazine]] ''Baltische Schachblätter''. In 1898 he established the Baltic Chess Society. Amelung published about 230 [[endgame studies]], making him the first chess historian in the Baltic States.<ref name=viljandi>{{cite web|title=23. märts - Friedrich Amelung 170|url=http://uudiskirjandus.blogspot.com/2012/03/23-marts-friedrich-amelung-170.html|publisher=Viljandi Linnaraamatukogu|accessdate=29 January 2013|language=Estonian|date=23 March 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304205124/http://uudiskirjandus.blogspot.com/2012/03/23-marts-friedrich-amelung-170.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=}}</ref>
He played a few games with [[Adolf Anderssen]], [[Gustav Neumann]], [[Carl Mayet]], [[Emil Schallopp]], [[Andreas Ascharin]], [[Emanuel Schiffers]].
He died in 1909 in [[Riga]] and is buried at the [[Kolga-Jaani]] cemetery in Estonia.<ref name=tea/>
